Vladimir Putin and the Risk of the Third World War
San Francisco — February 24, the Russian invasion of Ukraine marks the beginning of the third world war that could destroy our civilization.
Before the invasion, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping held a long meeting on February 4 — the day marking the start of the Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympic Games.
After the meeting, the two released a meticulously drafted 5,000-word document announcing the establishment of a close partnership between the two countries.
This document is stronger than any treaty and certainly requires detailed prior negotiations.
I was shocked that Xi seemed to have fully entrusted Putin to invade and wage war against Ukraine.
He thought that confirming himself as a lifelong ruler of China this下半年 was merely a formality, and he was definitely confident about it.
After concentrating all power in his own hands, Xi carefully planned a scheme to elevate himself to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
With Xi's support, Putin set about realizing his lifelong dream in an unimaginably brutal manner.
A 70-year-old Putin felt that if he wanted to leave a significant mark in Russian history, it would either be now or never.
But his view of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
He seems to believe that the Russian people need a tsar to blindly follow.
This system is entirely opposite to a democratic society, and this vision distorts the "soul" of the Russian people, emotional and sentimental to an extreme.
As a child, I had a lot of contact with Russian soldiers who occupied Hungary in 1945.
I know that if you ask them for something, they will share their last piece of bread with you.
Later, in the early 1980s, I launched what I call my political philanthropy.
Initially, I set up a foundation in my homeland, Hungary, and then I actively participated in activities that contributed to the dissolution of the Soviet Empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, this dissolution had already begun.
I also established foundations in Russia, and later in each of the newly independent republics.
In Ukraine, even before it became an independent country, I set up a foundation.
I also visited China in 1984 and became the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation (I closed this foundation in 1989, shortly after the Tiananmen Square massacre).
I personally do not know Putin, but I have been closely watching his rise and fully understand his cold and ruthless nature.
He reduced Grozny, the capital of Chechnya, to rubble, and now he threatens to do the same to Kyiv, the capital of Ukraine.
Putin was once a shrewd KGB agent, but lately he seems to have changed.
He seems to have lost touch with reality because he has formed a fixed notion.
There is no doubt that he misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He assumed that Russian-speaking Ukrainians would welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but the facts proved that they are no different from the Ukrainian-speaking population.
Despite the seemingly one-sided possibility, Ukrainian civilians still carried out an incredibly brave resistance.
In July 2021, Putin published a long article stating that Russians and Ukrainians are actually one nation, and that Ukrainians were misled by new Nazi agitators.
Since Kyiv is the original site of the Russian Orthodox Church, the first part of his argument is not without historical basis.
But in Part 2, it was Putin who was misled.
He should have been more aware of the facts.
Many Ukrainians bravely fought in the Euromaidan protests that erupted in 2014.
The 2014 events made him very angry.
Yet when ordered to attack his Ukrainian brothers, the Russian army performed poorly.
The entrenched corruption within the Ministry of Defense also played a significant role in this poor performance.
But Putin not only did not blame himself, but seemed to have gone mad.
He has resolved to punish Ukraine that opposes him, and his actions seem to have no constraints.
He threw the entire Russian army into battle and disregarded all rules of warfare, especially indiscriminately bombing civilian populations.
Many hospitals were attacked, and the power grid supplying the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant (currently occupied by Russian forces) was also destroyed.
In Mariupol, which is under siege, up to 400,000 people have had no water or food for nearly a week.
Russia is likely to lose this war.
Both the United States and the European Union are sending defensive weapons to Ukraine while trying to purchase Russian-made MIG fighter jets that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate.
These developments could change the entire situation.
Regardless of the outcome, Putin has created a miracle in strengthening European determination and unity.
At the same time, Xi seems to have realized that Putin has been unfaithful.
On March 8th, after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi firmly stated that the friendship between China and Russia remains "as solid as a rock," Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Scholz, expressing his support for their peacekeeping efforts.
In order to avoid a humanitarian crisis, he hopes to maintain maximum restraint during the war.
It is still uncertain whether Putin will accommodate Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be removed from power before they destroy our civilization.
